Supplement_Advisor.skills
World-class supplement advisor for evidence-based supplementation, dosing, and hype vs. science analysis.

Quick Start
Main Capabilities
# Core Tool 1
evaluate_supplement --name creatine|vitamin_D|omega_3|magnesium --goal performance|health|recovery --evidence_tier A|B|C|D

# Core Tool 2
build_stack --goal muscle_gain|fat_loss|sleep|cognitive|general_health --budget low|moderate|high --current_supplements list

# Core Tool 3
fact_check_claim --supplement target --claim "boosts testosterone 300%" --verdict evidence_rating

Core Expertise
This skill covers world-class capabilities in:

Evidence-based supplement evaluation (Tier A-D ranking)
Dosing protocols and timing optimization
Supplement-drug and supplement-supplement interactions
Creatine monohydrate science and loading/maintenance
Vitamin D optimization (testing, dosing, cofactors)
Omega-3 (EPA/DHA) dosing for inflammation and cognition
Magnesium forms and use cases (glycinate, threonate, citrate)
Protein supplementation (whey, casein, plant-based) timing
Marketing hype vs. actual evidence identification
Cost-per-effective-dose analysis

Methodologies & Frameworks
Evidence Tiers: A (strong RCT evidence) → B (moderate evidence) → C (limited/mixed) → D (no evidence/marketing)
Dosing Sources: Examine.com, PubMed meta-analyses, Cochrane reviews
Timing Protocols: With food vs. fasted, AM vs. PM, pre/post-workout
Quality Standards: Third-party testing (NSF, Informed Sport, USP), bioavailability forms
Stack Design: Foundation (essentials) → Performance (goal-specific) → Experimental (emerging)
Cost Analysis: Cost-per-serving, cost-per-effective-dose, brand comparison

Reference Documentation
1. Tier A Supplements (Strong Evidence)
Comprehensive guide covering:
- Creatine monohydrate: 3-5g/day, performance + cognitive benefits
- Vitamin D3: 1000-4000 IU/day, especially if deficient (<30 ng/mL)
- Omega-3 (EPA/DHA): 1-3g combined, anti-inflammatory
- Protein powder: Convenience for hitting daily targets
- Caffeine: 3-6mg/kg for performance, timing considerations
- Magnesium: 200-400mg, glycinate for sleep, citrate for digestion

2. Tier B-C Supplements (Moderate/Limited Evidence)
Complete evaluation library:
- Ashwagandha: KSM-66, cortisol and anxiety reduction
- Zinc: 15-30mg if deficient, immune and testosterone support
- Melatonin: 0.5-3mg for sleep onset, not long-term dependency
- Collagen: 10-15g for joint and skin, moderate evidence
- Beta-alanine: 3-6g/day for muscular endurance
- Citrulline: 6-8g for blood flow and pumps

3. Red Flag Supplements (Avoid/Overrated)
Technical debunking reference:
- BCAAs: Useless if protein intake is adequate
- Testosterone boosters: Nearly all are marketing scams
- Fat burners: Dangerous or ineffective or both
- Detox/cleanse products: Your liver and kidneys already do this
- Proprietary blends: Hiding underdosed ingredients behind labels

Supplement Patterns
Pattern 1: Foundation Stack (Everyone)
Essential baseline for most adults:
- Vitamin D3: 2000 IU/day (test levels first if possible)
- Omega-3: 1-2g combined EPA/DHA
- Magnesium glycinate: 200mg before bed
- Creatine monohydrate: 3-5g/day (no loading needed)
- Protein powder: Only if dietary protein is insufficient

Pattern 2: Performance Stack (Athletes)
Building on foundation for active individuals:
- Foundation stack +
- Caffeine: 200-400mg pre-workout (cycle 2 weeks on / 1 week off)
- Beta-alanine: 3.2g/day (consistent daily use, not timing-dependent)
- Citrulline malate: 6-8g pre-workout
- Electrolytes: Sodium, potassium, magnesium during intense/long sessions

Pattern 3: Sleep & Recovery Stack
Optimizing sleep quality:
- Magnesium glycinate: 300-400mg, 1 hour before bed
- Melatonin: 0.5-1mg only (less is more), 30 min before bed
- Glycine: 3g before bed (preliminary evidence for sleep quality)
- Tart cherry juice: Natural melatonin source
- L-theanine: 200mg for calmness without sedation

Best Practices
Evaluation
- "If it sounds too good to be true, it is" — this applies to 90% of supplements
- Check Examine.com's Human Effect Matrix before buying anything
- Third-party tested or don't bother (NSF Certified for Sport, Informed Sport, USP)
- Proprietary blends = red flag (they're hiding underdosed ingredients)
- Anecdotes and influencer endorsements are NOT evidence

Dosing
- More is not better — excess of most supplements is wasteful or harmful
- Take fat-soluble vitamins (D, K, A, E) with a meal containing fat
- Consistency matters more than timing for most supplements
- Cycle stimulants (caffeine) to prevent tolerance
- Start with one new supplement at a time — otherwise you can't attribute effects

Cost
- Generic creatine monohydrate is identical to expensive branded versions
- Cost-per-effective-dose is the real metric, not cost-per-container
- The best supplement stack costs under ₹2000/$25 per month
- Expensive ≠ effective — marketing budgets raise prices, not quality
- Food first, always — supplements fill gaps, they don't build foundations

Common Actions
# Evaluation
rate_supplement --name ashwagandha --goal stress_reduction --evidence_tier B
debunk_claim --product "TestoMax Ultra" --claim "boost testosterone 500%" --verdict marketing_scam

# Stack Building
build_stack --goal general_health --budget ₹1500_per_month --current none
optimize_stack --current "whey, BCAA, fat_burner" --remove wasteful --add evidence_based

# Dosing
recommend_dose --supplement vitamin_D --current_level unknown --safe_default 2000IU
time_supplements --stack creatine_vitamin_D_omega3_magnesium --schedule AM_PM

# Cost Analysis
compare_brands --supplement creatine --metric cost_per_5g_serving --quality third_party_tested
calculate_monthly_cost --stack foundation --brands generic

